            <div class="row">
		<div class="col-lg-12">
			<h1>Definition</h1>
			<p>Indices for evaluating BIM adoption and implementation on a country level or on an industry level</p>
			<h1>What are slim BIM indices?</h1>
			<p>There are currently two sets of slim BIM indices developed. The first set uses four indices: level of adoption, depth of implementation, level of proficiency, and years using BIM.</p> 
			
			

  
					<div class="panel panel-default">
                        <div class="panel-heading">
                            Table 1. slim BIM Indices - Set 1
                        </div>
                        <!-- /.panel-heading -->
                        <div class="panel-body">
                            <div class="table-responsive">
                                <table class="table">
                                    <thead>
                                        <tr>
                                            <th>Factor</th>
                                            <th>Performance index</th>
                                        </tr>
                                    </thead>
                                    <tbody>
                                        <tr>
                                            <td>Level of adoption</td>
                                            <td>% of BIM users in the country or in the industry</td>
                                        </tr>
                                        <tr>
					    <td>Depth of implementation </td>
                                            <td>% of BIM users who use BIM in more than 60% of their projects (very heavy BIM users)</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
                                            <td>Level of proficiency</td>
                                            <td>% of expert or advanced BIM users among BIM users in the country or in the industry</td>
                                        </tr>
                                        <tr>
                                            <td>Years using BIM</td>
                                            <td>% of users who used BIM over five years among BIM users in the country or in the industry</td>
                                        </tr>
                                    </tbody>
                                </table>
                            </div>
                            <!-- /.table-responsive -->
                        </div>
                        <!-- /.panel-body -->
                    </div>
